data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>` which safely checks the type and gives you the typed reference:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    // MSTest 3.x (out parameter)
    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result, out var handler);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);

    // MSTest 4.x (returns directly)
    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

This is better because:
- No `InvalidCastException` — you get a clear test failure if the type is wrong
- The failure message tells you the actual vs. expected type
- No separate null check needed — it's implicit
